result.execSummary:
The defendant Chazz Deandrew White was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of THC (2nd+ Offense), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(e).
  • Possession of Controlled Substance, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: As to COUNT 1 and COUNT 2, pay all mandatory court costs, fees, assessments and surcharges, including DNA surcharge, during the course of probation to the probation agent. Any remaining balance due at the end of probation will become immediately due or civil judgment to be entered.
Obtain/maintain full time employment/school or a combination of both.

No possession of any firearms or weapons, firearm ammunition, firearm holster, or any body armor.
Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions: Firearm possession and Voting.

No use or possession of controlled substances without a valid prescription, taken in the manner and fashion as prescribed.
No possession of any drug paraphernalia for personal use, manufacturing, delivering, or for distribution.

Defendant to complete Parenting or Fatherhood program.
Defendant to provide a DNA sample, if not already done.

Defendant to participate in Alcohol and Drug assessment and successfully complete recommended treatment including drug and alcohol testing.
Maintain absolute sobriety.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Chazz Deandrew White in court with attorney Ann T. Bowe.  Paul M. Hauer appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.

AS TO COUNT 1:
Court ordered defendant to serve 160 DAYS in the House of Correction consecutive to any other sentence; release to the Day Reporting Center only; credit for 0 days time served. Court remains silent as to electronic monitoring.
Court approved participation in Dosage Probation Pilot Program and early termination of probation if defendant successfully completes program and all other conditions of probation.  
Court STAYED the sentence and placed defendant on probation for 2 YEARS.

AS TO COUNT 2:
Court ordered defendant to serve 30 DAYS in the House of Correction concurrent to COUNT 1 and consecutive to any other sentence; release to the Day Reporting Center only; credit for 0 days time served. Court remains silent as to electronic monitoring.
Court STAYED the sentence and placed defendant on probation for 1 YEAR.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION:
- As to COUNT 1 and COUNT 2, Pay all mandatory court costs, fees, assessments 
  and surcharges, including the DNA surcharge, during the course of probation to the probation agent. 
  Any remaining balance due at the end of probation will become immediately due
  or civil judgment to be entered. 
- Maintain Absolute Sobriety, no alcohol.
- No use or possession of controlled substances without a valid 
  prescription taken in the manner and fashion as prescribed.
- Defendant to participate in Alcohol and Drug Assessment
  and successfully complete recommended treatment
  including drug and alcohol testing. 
- Obtain/Maintain Full Time employment/school or a combination of both. 
- No possession of any drug paraphernalia for personal use, manufacturing, delivering or for distribution.
- No possession of any firearms or weapons, firearm ammunition, firearm holster, or any body armor.
- Defendant to complete Parenting or Fatherhood program.
- Defendant to provide DNA sample, if not already done.

Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.

Appellate rights notice given to the defendant.
